
  The French government Saturday announced several emergency measures to support the jobless people, including sending an additional 500 million franc (84 million U.S. dollars) unemployment aid package.
  The unemployment rate in France dropped by 0.3 percent to stand at 12.4 percent in November, said the Ministry of Employment Tuesday.
  Meanwhile, Minister of Labor, Employment and Social Affairs Jacques Barrot said today that the government will subsidize 15-20 billion francs (3-4 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997 to finance employment programs.
  France's unemployment rate dropped by 1.6 percent in December last year, reducing the nation's jobless people to 2,583,600, said the Ministry of Employment Friday.
  The 12.5 percent unemployment rate is haunting the Christmas season in France as militants and unionists staged several protests over the past week against unemployment.
  While recognizing the social performance of the welfare system of France, the OECD also expressed worry over the high costs of France's social protection system, in particular the high cost of unemployment insurance and unemployment compensation rates.
  The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) today called on France to adopt more flexible socio-economic policies in its on-going structural reforms.
  France and especially West Germany also had a history of keeping unemployment low in the 1960s and early 1970s.
  French President Jacques Chirac said Monday that the government should be `particularly careful` about the problem of social exclusion, which results from long time unemployment.
  The EU is already paying 200 billion ECU (229 billion U.S. dollars) each year in unemployment allowances.

